Hwang Kyo-ahn

Last Modified: 2025-09-28 02:22:45

1. Overview

Hwang Kyo-ahn is a South Korean politician with a background in law and government service.

He served as a public security prosecutor, Chief Prosecutor of the Busan High Prosecutors’ Office, Minister of Justice, and the 44th Prime Minister. He was the second leader of the Liberty Korea Party (predecessor to the People Power Party) and the founding leader of the United Future Party. Following President Park Geun-hye’s impeachment, he served as Acting President of South Korea for about five months until Moon Jae-in took office. After leaving the People Power Party, he ran as an independent candidate in the 2025 presidential election and founded the Freedom and Innovation Party in July 2025, becoming its leader.

2. Early Life

Born on April 15, 1957, in Yongsan District, Seoul, he was the youngest of six children. After failing to enter Seoul National University’s law school despite multiple attempts, he enrolled at Sungkyunkwan University as part of the class of ’77. He passed the 23rd bar exam in 1981 and was appointed prosecutor in Cheongju in 1983. Later, he joined the public security division of the Seoul District Prosecutors’ Office, earning the nickname 'Mr. National Security Law'. He served as Chief Prosecutor in Daegu and Busan, published a book titled National Security Law, and retired from prosecution in September 2011 to work as a legal advisor at law firm Taepyeongyang.

In 2013, he was appointed Minister of Justice under the Park Geun-hye administration. On November 5, 2013, he filed a petition with the Constitutional Court to dissolve the Unified Progressive Party, gaining public attention. After the court approved the dissolution, he was appointed Prime Minister in 2015. During the 2016 South Korean political scandal, he became Acting President following Park’s impeachment. He resigned as Prime Minister on May 10, 2017, when Moon Jae-in was elected president. After stepping down, he voiced political opinions via Facebook and supported Liberty Korea Party candidates in the 2018 local elections.

On January 15, 2019, he joined the Liberty Korea Party, declaring the country was in 'total crisis' and vowing to correct the Moon administration’s economic failures. He ran for party leader and won with 50.1% of the vote. As a leader, he adopted a more direct and aggressive tone in criticizing Moon Jae-in, contrasting with his previously reserved image. During the Cho Kuk scandal, he shaved his head in protest and staged a hunger strike in front of the Cheong Wa Dae to rally core supporters.

In 2020, the Liberty Korea Party merged with the New Conservative Party to form the United Future Party, and Hwang became its first leader. Responding to calls to run in a difficult district, he entered the 2020 general election in Jongno, Seoul, against Lee Nak-yon, but suffered a crushing defeat with less than 40% of the vote.

3. Post-2020 Activities

As vote counts revealed the United Future Party’s defeat, Hwang held a press conference to concede and resigned from all positions. He remained largely out of the spotlight as the party rebranded to the People Power Party, but reentered politics in July 2021 by announcing his presidential bid. During the primary, he promoted election fraud conspiracy theories, including calls for a recount of the 2020 general election, but failed to place in the top four and was eliminated. Afterward, he continued to claim fraud in the People Power Party’s primary and, following his defeat in the 2023 party leadership race, he claimed fraud again and became a leading figure in South Korea’s 2020s election fraud conspiracy movement.

In 2024, when President Yoon Suk-yeol declared emergency martial law on December 3, Hwang expressed support and called for the arrest of National Assembly Speaker Woo Won-shik and People Power Party leader Han Dong-hoon. He served as a defense attorney for Yoon during his impeachment trial. After the Constitutional Court ruled to remove Yoon from office, Hwang left the People Power Party and ran as an independent in the 2025 presidential election, but withdrew mid-race to endorse Kim Moon-soo. As of late September 2025, he was sentenced to a 1 year and 6 month prison sentence for violating the National Assembly Act, with a first trial verdict scheduled for November 20.

4. Evaluation

Lee Nak-yon

Last Modified: 2025-09-28 16:20:41

1. Overview

Lee Nak-yon is a South Korean politician who began his career as a journalist.

He worked as a reporter for the Dong-A Ilbo before entering politics in 2000 by winning a seat in the National Assembly. He has served as Floor Leader of the Millennium Democratic Party, the 37th Governor of South Jeolla Province, the 45th Prime Minister, a five-term lawmaker (16th-19th, 21st National Assembly), the 4th leader of the Democratic Party, and the inaugural co-leader of New Future Party. He currently serves as Senior Advisor to the New Future Democratic Party.

2. Early Life

Born on December 20, 1952, in Yeonggwang County, South Jeolla Province, he was the eldest of seven siblings. In sixth grade, his homeroom teacher recognized his intelligence and persuaded his impoverished parents to send him to middle school in Gwangju. His mother supported him by farming and selling vegetables. He graduated from Gwangju Bukseong Middle School, Gwangju Jeil High School, and Seoul National University’s College of Law. After college, he served 31 months in the Korean Army as a KATUSA administrative clerk, discharged as a sergeant in 1976. He initially prepared for the bar exam but gave up due to financial hardship and briefly worked at Korea Investment Trust before joining Dong-A Ilbo as a journalist in 1979.

At Dong-A Ilbo, he worked as a political reporter, Tokyo correspondent, editorial writer, and head of the international desk. During his time as a journalist, he built a relationship with Kim Dae-jung, then leader of the Peace Democratic Party, who encouraged him to enter politics. Although he initially declined, preferring his Tokyo post, he eventually ran in the 2000 general election as a Millennium Democratic Party candidate in Hampyeong-Yeonggwang district and won. He was elected four consecutive times in his hometown of Yeonggwang and served five terms as party spokesperson, earning the nickname 'Five-Term Spokesman'. In 2014, he resigned from the National Assembly and was elected Governor of South Jeolla Province. While serving as governor, he was appointed by President Moon Jae-in as the first Prime Minister of the Moon administration in 2017.

As Prime Minister, he was praised by Democratic supporters for his eloquence and leadership, and emerged as a leading liberal presidential contender against Hwang Kyo-ahn. He served a record 2 years and 7 months, the longest term for a Prime Minister since democratization, and stepped down in January 2020. Shortly after, he met with Democratic Party leader Lee Hae-chan and ran in the 2020 general election in Jongno District, Seoul, as co-chair of the campaign committee. His active campaigning led to a landslide victory over Hwang Kyo-ahn with nearly 60% of the vote, contributing to the Democratic Party’s sweeping win.

3. Post-2020 Activities

After the election, he ran for Democratic Party leader and won by a wide margin. Early in his term, he was seen as the likely presidential nominee, but support for hardliner Gyeonggi Governor Lee Jae-myung surged, putting Lee Nak-yon in a difficult position. His 2021 New Year’s proposal to pardon former Presidents Lee Myung-bak and Park Geun-hye sparked backlash within the party and caused his approval ratings to plummet. He eventually resigned as party leader and ran in the Democratic primary with backing from pro-Moon factions, but lost to Lee Jae-myung with only 39% of the vote.

After his defeat, he left for the United States in June 2022 and spent a year as a visiting scholar at George Washington University. Upon returning, he demanded Lee Jae-myung’s resignation as party leader, and when that failed, he left the Democratic Party in January 2024 and founded the New Future Party, becoming its co-leader. He ran in the 2024 general election in Gwangju Gwangsan B district but suffered a crushing defeat with just 13% of the vote. He did not run in the 2025 presidential election, instead endorsing People Power Party candidate Kim Moon-soo, citing the need to stop Lee Jae-myung’s 'dictatorship'. This drew heavy criticism from Democratic figures, and after Lee Jae-myung won the presidency, Lee Nak-yon’s political future became uncertain. His September 2025 meeting with former President Moon Jae-in and his wife sparked criticism, highlighting his complete estrangement from the Democratic Party.

Lee Jae-myung

Last Modified: 2025-09-30 02:36:41

1. Overview

Lee Jae-myung is the 21st President of the Republic of Korea.

He began his career as a lawyer and civic activist, and was elected mayor of Seongnam in the 2010 local elections. After winning re-election in 2014, he became Governor of Gyeonggi Province in 2018. He ran in the 2022 presidential election but finished second. Following the vacancy left by President Yoon Suk-yeol in 2025, Lee ran again in the 2025 presidential election and won. He is scheduled to serve as president until June 3, 2030.

2. Early Life

Lee was born around October 1963 in Andong County, North Gyeongsang Province. Due to poverty, his mother never recorded his exact birth date, and even Lee himself does not know it. After finishing elementary school, he moved to Seongnam, Gyeonggi Province, and instead of attending middle school, he worked in a factory as a child laborer. He suffered multiple accidents during this time, resulting in a disability in his left arm and severe depression, even attempting suicide at age 17. Passing the middle school equivalency exam helped him overcome his depression and begin preparing for college. In 1982, he was admitted to Chung-Ang University’s law department with a full tuition waiver. After graduating, he passed the bar exam in 1986 and opened a law office in Seongnam.

While working as a lawyer and activist, he began to feel the limits of legal advocacy and decided to enter politics in 2004. He ran for mayor of Seongnam in the 2006 local elections but lost, and again lost in the 2008 general election for the Seongnam Bundang A district. In 2010, he ran again for Seongnam mayor and won, then secured re-election in 2014 with a higher vote share. His strong performance as mayor raised his national profile in the mid-2010s, and he began to be seen as a presidential contender.

After the Park Geun-hye scandal broke in 2016, Lee was among the early voices calling for Park’s resignation, gaining public support. He ran in the 2017 presidential election following Park’s impeachment but placed third in the Democratic Party primary. In 2018, he ran for Governor of Gyeonggi Province and won with 56.4% of the vote, defeating incumbent Nam Kyung-pil of the Liberty Korea Party. This made him the first Democratic governor of Gyeonggi in 20 years since 1998.

3. Post-2020 Activities

Lee’s administrative performance as governor earned praise from Democratic Party members, and by early 2020, he reemerged as a strong presidential hopeful. He competed with then-party leader Lee Nak-yon in polls through late 2020, and in 2021, benefited from Lee Nak-yon’s decline to win the party’s nomination. However, in the 2022 presidential election, he lost to People Power Party candidate Yoon Suk-yeol by a margin of 0.73 percentage points. Shortly after, he won a by-election and became a member of the National Assembly, later serving as Democratic Party leader.

During his tenure as party leader, he was indicted on multiple charges by prosecutors, facing what was dubbed a 'judicial risk'. This led to persistent calls for resignation from within the party, but he held on and led the Democratic Party to victory in the 2024 general election. He also spearheaded the lifting of President Yoon’s martial law declaration and pushed for Yoon’s impeachment, solidifying his status as the leading presidential candidate. After Yoon’s removal from office, Lee ran in the 2025 presidential election and won with 49.42% of the vote, defeating People Power Party candidate Kim Moon-soo. He was inaugurated as the 21st President of South Korea on June 4, 2025.

4. Evaluation

Choo Mi-ae

Last Modified: 2025-09-30 21:28:44

1. Overview

Choo Mi-ae is a South Korean politician and former judge.

She passed the bar exam in 1982 and served as a judge before entering politics in 1995, recruited by then-opposition leader Kim Dae-jung. She was elected five times as a member of the National Assembly for Gwangjin B district in Seoul, served as leader of the Democratic Party, and was appointed Minister of Justice under President Moon Jae-in. In the 2024 general election, she ran in Gyeonggi Province’s Hanam A district and won, becoming the most elected female lawmaker in South Korean history. She currently serves as Chair of the National Assembly’s Legislation and Judiciary Committee.

2. Early Life

Born on October 23, 1958, in Dalseong County, North Gyeongsang Province, Choo was the second child of parents who ran a laundry business. After a burglary at the family shop when she was three, she was sent to live with her maternal grandparents due to financial hardship. She completed high school in Daegu and entered Hanyang University’s law department, passing the bar exam in 1982. At the time, she was one of only three female passers and drew attention for not being a Seoul National University graduate. She began her judicial career at Chuncheon District Court and later served at Incheon District Court and Gwangju High Court.

While working at the Gwangju High Court in 1995, she was invited by Kim Dae-jung to enter politics. She resigned from the bench that year and was elected to the National Assembly in 1996. During the 1997 presidential election, she campaigned in her hometown of Daegu to support Kim Dae-jung, naming her campaign team the 'Jeanne d’Arc Squad' to challenge regionalism, and supporters nicknamed her 'Choo d’Arc'. She also helped raise campaign funds for Roh Moo-hyun in 2002, contributing to his victory. However, after clashing with President Roh, she voted in favor of his impeachment in 2004. This led to backlash from liberal voters and her defeat in that year’s general election. She returned to the National Assembly in 2008.

She served multiple terms as a senior party official and became a five-term lawmaker. In 2016, she was elected leader of the Democratic Party, recognized for supporting Moon Jae-in during a leadership crisis and promoting party unity. After Moon’s presidential victory in 2017, Choo became the first female leader of a ruling party in South Korean history. She stepped down as party leader and was appointed Minister of Justice in 2020.

3. Post-2020 Activities

As Minister of Justice, Choo advocated for prosecutorial reform and clashed fiercely with then-Prosecutor General Yoon Suk-yeol. She attempted to discipline Yoon, but the courts blocked the move, leading to her resignation. As Yoon gained popularity among conservative voters and emerged as a major presidential contender, some critics mockingly called Choo his 'X-man', suggesting she had inadvertently boosted his career. She declared her candidacy for the 2022 presidential race and competed in the Democratic primary against Lee Nak-yon and Lee Jae-myung, finishing third. Having not run in the 2020 general election, she held no official positions and withdrew from politics for about a year after Yoon’s election in 2022.

However, as Yoon’s approval ratings plummeted, Choo regained prominence as his strongest rival. She was strategically nominated to run in the competitive Hanam A district in the 2024 general election and won, becoming the first Korean woman to serve six terms in the National Assembly. She ran for Speaker of the Assembly but lost to fellow party member Woo Won-shik. After the martial law crisis in December 2024, she obtained and released documents suggesting prior planning and led the investigation as head of the Special Committee for Truth-Finding on Rebellion. Following Lee Jae-myung’s presidential victory in 2025, Choo was appointed as Special Envoy to the UK and was elected Chair of the Legislation and Judiciary Committee in August 2025, a role she continues to hold.

Cho Kuk

Last Modified: 2025-09-30 23:45:30

1. Overview

Cho Kuk is a South Korean politician and former legal scholar.

He earned a J.S.D. from UC Berkeley School of Law and taught at Ulsan University, Dongguk University, and Seoul National University (SNU). While at SNU, he gained public attention through various social activities. Under President Moon Jae-in, he served as Senior Presidential Secretary for Civil Affairs and Minister of Justice. In 2024, he entered politics, founded the Rebuilding Korea Party, became its first leader, and was elected to the 22nd National Assembly as a proportional representative. He currently serves as the party’s Emergency Committee Chair.

2. Early Life

Born on April 6, 1965, in Busan, Cho is the eldest son of a businessman father and a teacher mother. He entered SNU’s Department of Public Law in 1982. During college, he joined the South Korean Socialist Workers’ Alliance at the suggestion of the student council president, leading to a brief arrest in 1993. After earning his master’s in law from SNU, he studied abroad at UC Berkeley, receiving his doctorate in 1997. He returned to Korea and taught law at Ulsan University in 1999, Dongguk University in 2000, and SNU from 2001, eventually becoming a full professor at SNU Law School.

On May 11, 2017, he was appointed Senior Secretary for Civil Affairs in the Moon administration, overseeing vetting of high-ranking officials. He also responded to Cheong Wa Dae petitions. In August 2019, he was nominated as Minister of Justice, but faced fierce opposition from the conservative Liberty Korea Party. During his confirmation hearings, allegations of academic fraud involving his family surfaced. Despite public division, Moon appointed him anyway. However, amid protests and backlash from prosecutors, Cho resigned in October 2019. After stepping down, he faced an investigation and a trial. He attempted to return to SNU, but was suspended in January 2020 due to concerns over students’ rights.

3. Post-2020 Activities

Despite ongoing investigations, Cho continued expressing political views on Facebook. In March 2022, he moved to the Gwanak District near SNU and published a book titled 'A Stroll Through Legal Classics', signaling political ambitions. After prosecutors demanded a 5-year sentence in December 2022, he was sentenced to 2 years in February 2023. Declaring his intent to 'bring down the Yoon Suk-yeol administration', he announced his candidacy for the 2024 general election. Instead of joining the Democratic Party, he founded the Rebuilding Korea Party. The party didn’t field district candidates but targeted proportional votes from Democratic supporters - a strategy that succeeded, electing 12 members, including Cho himself.

Following President Yoon’s martial law crisis, Cho pushed hard for impeachment. On December 12, 2024, the Supreme Court upheld his 2-year sentence, stripping him of his seat. After receiving a delay in sentence execution, he witnessed Yoon’s impeachment on December 14. He then stated, 'My role is complete,' and entered Seoul Detention Center. After Lee Jae-myung was elected president, Cho was pardoned and reinstated in August 2025. He rejoined his party and was appointed Emergency Committee Chair. Polls now place him among the leading presidential contenders alongside Democratic Party leader Jung Chung-rae and Prime Minister Kim Min-seok.

Yoon Suk-yeol

Last Modified: 2025-10-01 23:47:49

1. Overview

Yoon Suk-yeol is the 20th President of the Republic of Korea.

He graduated from Seoul National University’s College of Law and passed the bar exam on his ninth attempt, becoming a prosecutor. He joined the special investigation team for the 2016 Park Geun-hye scandal and was appointed as the 43rd Prosecutor General under the Moon Jae-in administration in 2019. However, following the Cho Kuk scandal shortly after his appointment, he launched investigations targeting the Moon administration, sparking conflict and criticizing its prosecutorial reforms. He resigned in 2021 and declared his candidacy for the 2022 presidential election, winning the People Power Party primary and defeating Democratic Party candidate Lee Jae-myung in 2022. His presidency was plagued by continuous crises, culminating in his declaration of martial law on December 3, 2024, which was overturned by the National Assembly. He was subsequently impeached and removed from office by unanimous decision of the Constitutional Court in April 2025.

2. Early Life

Born on December 18, 1960, in Seongbuk District, Seoul. After graduating from Choongam High School in 1979, he entered Seoul National University’s law school. In a mock trial held in 1980, he sentenced Chun Doo-hwan to life imprisonment - a moment that resurfaced when he entered politics. Due to anisometropia, he was classified for wartime labor service instead of active military duty. While attending graduate school, he prepared for the bar exam but struggled due to limited study time compared to other candidates. He passed on his ninth attempt in 1991 and began his career as a prosecutor in Daegu in 1994. In 2002, he briefly left the prosecution to work as a lawyer at the law firm Taepyeongyang but returned in 2003, feeling the role didn’t suit him.

In 2013, he led the special investigation into the National Intelligence Service’s opinion manipulation scandal, conducting aggressive raids that shook the Park administration. He clashed with then-Minister of Justice Hwang Kyo-ahn and gained public attention for stating, 'I don’t pledge loyalty to a specific person' during a parliamentary hearing. He was demoted to regional posts under Park but returned as a lead investigator in the 2016 Park scandal. After Moon Jae-in’s election in 2017, he was promoted to head of the Seoul Central District Prosecutors’ Office and led the investigation that resulted in the arrest of former President Lee Myung-bak. In July 2019, Moon appointed him Prosecutor General.

Soon after, the Cho Kuk scandal erupted. Defying expectations, Yoon ordered sweeping investigations and raids targeting Cho. He also launched probes into various allegations involving the Cheong Wa Dae, leading to a rift with the Moon administration. Critics accused him of opposing prosecutorial reform and targeting Cho for political reasons, while supporters claimed he was simply investigating abuses of power.

3. Post-2020 Activities

Although the Democratic Party’s landslide victory in the 2020 general election seemed to sideline him, Yoon gained popularity among opposition supporters during his conflict with Justice Minister Choo Mi-ae. Her attempt to discipline him was blocked by the courts. In March 2021, Yoon resigned, pledging to defend liberal democracy and the people. After continued engagement with People Power Party figures, he declared his presidential bid in June 2021, joined the PPP in July, and won the primary over Rep. Hong Joon-pyo. Despite internal party strife and controversies over his remarks, he unified with People’s Party candidate Ahn Cheol-soo and narrowly defeated Lee Jae-myung by 0.73 percentage points in March 2022.

He led the party to victory in the 2022 local elections, but scandals - including the ousting of party leader Lee Jun-seok - caused his approval ratings to plummet within three months. By the 2024 general election, his popularity had not recovered, and the People Power Party suffered a major defeat, winning only 108 seats. Post-election, a wave of scandals and impeachment calls emerged. On December 3, 2024, he declared martial law in an attempt to regain control, but the National Assembly passed a resolution to lift it within two hours. Park Yong-jin

Last Modified: 2025-10-02 09:50:47

1. Overview

Park Yong-jin is a South Korean politician who began his career as a labor activist.

While studying at Sungkyunkwan University, he actively participated in student movements and later committed himself to labor activism after graduation. In 1997, he was dispatched to the progressive party People’s Victory for 21st Century, working under Kwon Young-ghil, and later served as spokesperson for the Democratic Labor Party. He joined the Democratic United Party in 2011, serving as party spokesperson, and was elected to the National Assembly in 2016 as a Democratic Party candidate for Gangbuk B district in Seoul. He was re-elected in 2020 and ran in the presidential primary, finishing fourth. After the presidential election, he ran against Lee Jae-myung in the party leadership race but lost. Despite maintaining a critical stance toward Lee, Park was defeated in the party primary for the 2024 general election. However, during the 2025 presidential campaign, he was appointed Chair of the National Unity Committee by Lee Jae-myung and supported his election. After Lee’s victory, Park was included in the presidential delegation to Australia.

2. Early Life

Park was born on April 17, 1971, in Jangsu County, North Jeolla Province, the third of four children. His family later moved to nearby Jeonju, where he entered elementary school. In second grade, his father’s job transfer brought the family to Seoul, where Park completed high school in Gangbuk District. In his second year of high school, his homeroom teacher was arrested for helping found the Korean Teachers and Education Workers Union in 1989, prompting Park to lead student protests. He entered Sungkyunkwan University’s sociology department in 1990 and became involved in progressive student activism. In 1994, he was elected president of the student council and was arrested while supporting a solidarity strike by railway and subway unions, spending over 100 days in detention. After receiving a suspended sentence, he served in the military and, upon graduation, was dispatched to People’s Victory for 21st Century as head of media under Kwon Young-ghil.

He supported Kwon’s 1997 presidential campaign and continued working in progressive politics, holding roles such as head of planning, organization, and personal secretary. After People’s Victory for 21st Century dissolved in 1999, Park joined its successor, the Democratic Labor Party, and ran for the National Assembly in Gangbuk B district in 2000, earning 13.3% of the vote. He was elected to the party’s national executive committee and participated in protests against mass layoffs at Daewoo Motors in 2001, resulting in a 2-year and 1-month prison sentence. After being pardoned by President Roh Moo-hyun, he was appointed party spokesperson and remained active until 2008, when he left to help found the New Progressive Party.

In 2010, Park served as vice leader of the New Progressive Party and advocated for unifying the progressive opposition. When party unification failed, he left the New Progressive Party in 2011 and joined the Democratic United Party. From 2012 to 2014, he served as party spokesperson, earning the nickname 'the voice of the Democratic Party'. He ran again in Gangbuk B district in 2016 and was finally elected. In the National Assembly, he served on the Special Committee for Political Reform and led the passage of the 'Three Kindergarten Laws'. In the 2020 election, he was re-elected with 64.45% of the vote - the highest among Democratic candidates in Seoul.

3. Post-2020 Activities

Although a member of the Democratic Party, Park remained part of its non-mainstream faction and criticized the Moon administration’s North Korea and housing policies. In 2021, he declared his candidacy for president and attacked Lee Jae-myung during the party primary, but finished fourth with 1.55% of the vote. After the primary, he joined Lee’s campaign as co-chair but ran against him in the 2022 party leadership race. Park criticized Lee’s personal fanbase politics and called for 'a Democratic Party governed by public sentiment and common sense', but his overly negative campaigning led to poor reception among party members, and he lost with just 22.23% of the vote.

He continued to criticize Lee’s leadership without aligning with any faction, earning a negative reputation among pro-Lee members. In 2024, he was ranked in the bottom 10% of legislative performance and lost the party primary in Gangbuk B district. In a post-election interview, he revealed he had undergone surgery for oral cancer during the primary. On December 3, 2024, when President Yoon Suk-yeol declared martial law, Park, despite not being a sitting lawmaker, joined citizens at the National Assembly to block military entry. In 2025, he reconciled with Lee Jae-myung and served as Chair of the National Unity Committee in Lee’s presidential campaign. He now appears as a panelist on political talk shows, criticizing the People Power Party and advising the Lee administration.

Ryu Si-min

Last Modified: 2025-10-02 10:38:21

1. Overview

Ryu Si-min is a South Korean writer and broadcaster who formerly served as a politician.

After graduating from Seoul National University with a degree in economics, he studied abroad in Germany and earned a master’s degree in health economics. Upon returning to Korea, he became a writer and political commentator, publishing works such as 'A Reverse Reading of World History'. He entered politics by founding the Reformist National Party and later joined President Roh Moo-hyun in establishing the Uri Party. He served as a member of the 16th and 17th National Assembly and as the 44th Minister of Health and Welfare. Following Roh’s death in 2009, Ryu was considered a leading presidential candidate for the Democratic Party, but his defeat to Kim Moon-soo in the 2010 Gyeonggi gubernatorial race weakened his political standing. He retired from politics in 2013 and has since focused on writing, publishing multiple bestsellers. He now appears regularly on current affairs programs as a writer and media personality.

2. Early Life

Ryu was born on July 28, 1959, in Wolseong County, North Gyeongsang Province (now Gyeongju), to a father who was a teacher and a mother who ran a small shop. He spent his school years in Daegu and later entered Seoul National University’s economics department. In 1980, he became chair of the university’s student council and participated in protests at Seoul Station demanding the resignation of Chun Doo-hwan and the military regime. After completing his military service in 1983, he continued student activism as chair of the SNU returning students’ council and a member of the Seoul Labor Movement Union. Due to his activism, he was placed on a wanted list. In 1988, he accepted an offer from then-Peace Democratic Party lawmaker Lee Hae-chan to work as a legislative aide, marking his first political experience. During this time, he privately criticized Kim Dae-jung’s 'mercantile' political style. After graduating from SNU in 1991, he left his aide position in 1992 and studied in Germany, earning a master’s in health economics.

During his five years abroad, he frequently returned to Korea and built a close relationship with Roh Moo-hyun, sharing economic insights. After returning in 1997, he worked as a political commentator and controversially predicted Kim Dae-jung’s defeat in the presidential election. Even after Kim’s victory, Ryu criticized the Democratic Party’s lack of reform. In the 2002 presidential election, when Roh faced internal opposition, Ryu declared that 'saving Roh Moo-hyun is political reform itself', and transitioned into full-time politics at Roh’s request, founding the Reformist National Party. He was elected in a 2003 by-election in Goyang Deogyang A district, Gyeonggi Province, and joined the newly formed Uri Party, winning re-election in 2004.

In 2006, President Roh appointed him Minister of Health and Welfare. After stepping down in 2007, Ryu declared his candidacy for president but withdrew during the Grand Unified Democratic New Party’s primary. He ran as an independent in Daegu’s Suseong B district in the 2008 general election but lost. In 2010, he founded the Participation Party and ran for governor of Gyeonggi Province, again losing to Kim Moon-soo. He joined the Unified Progressive Party in 2011 and served as co-leader, but internal factional strife led him to retire from politics in 2013 and focus on writing and commentary. He published bestsellers such as 'How Should We Live', 'My Modern Korean History', 'Ryu Si-min’s Writing Lecture', and 'The History of History'. In 2018, he became chair of the Roh Moo-hyun Foundation and launched the podcast Ryu Si-min’s Alileo in 2019, which gained 500,000 YouTube subscribers within three days.

3. Post-2020 Activities

Though rumors of a political comeback surfaced during the Moon Jae-in administration, Ryu firmly denied them and did not run in any elections. Just before the 2020 general election, he predicted that the liberal bloc would win 180 seats - a forecast that proved accurate but was criticized for galvanizing conservative voters. Feeling responsible, he suspended political commentary until late 2021. During the 2022 presidential race, he predicted a narrow 1% victory for Democratic candidate Lee Jae-myung, but Yoon Suk-yeol won instead. Ryu appeared as a panelist on KBS’s election coverage and offered words of consolation to Lee. He continues to appear on various broadcasts as a political commentator and is now considered one of the most influential media figures among Democratic supporters.

2027 South Korean presidential election - Wikipedia

The 2027 South Korean presidential election was held on March 3, 2027, to elect the 21st president of South Korea. In the election, Democratic Party lawmaker Lee Kwang-jae defeated former United Future Party leader Won Hee-ryong and former Unification Minister Min Kyung-wook of the Fair Election Party to become president.

Key issues in the race included calls to abolish early voting, the rise of far-right factions, deteriorating Korea-China relations, internal divisions within the conservative bloc, low birth rates and aging demographics, and the decline of non-metropolitan regions.

Struggling to maintain composure, he was hit with another blow: multiple broadcasters had designated Suseong B as a key race and sent reporters to his campaign office, which meant his reaction to the exit polls was broadcast live nationwide. Even in his 2017 presidential defeat, Hong had managed a smile, but this time, he looked like his soul had left his body.


One by one, major broadcasters declare Hwang the likely winner.


But if that were the end of the story, we wouldn’t be talking about it here. About 30 minutes after the exit polls were released, KBS began live coverage from Hong’s campaign office. A reporter stood in front of the camera, describing the somber mood and people watching the vote count. Then, Hong gave a quiet instruction to a staffer:

'Play it.'

When did you stop like that…

Suddenly, the old rock ballad 'The Cloudburst' by Boohwal blasted through the room, drowning out the reporter’s voice. The startled announcer and reporter were briefly shown on air before the live feed was cut. The announcer apologized to viewers for the 'inappropriate footage'. Why such a fuss? Because the song had been banned from KBS broadcasts.


Projections gradually shift from 'likely' to 'confirmed'.


In late 2023, after a new president took over KBS, the public broadcaster conducted a sweeping review of pop songs and banned dozens. One of them was 'The Cloudburst'. Officially, the reason was that the singer had a history of marijuana use, aligning with the Hwang administration’s crackdown on drugs. But everyone knew that was just an excuse. In reality, 'The Cloudburst' - with lyrics mourning someone who left too soon - had become a kind of anthem among Democratic supporters after Ryu Si-min’s defeat. As it gained popularity and was embraced as a protest song, KBS banned it to appease the administration.

Hong had planned this performance in advance. Whether he won or lost, he wanted to make Hwang Kyo-ahn clutch his neck, and it worked. Within minutes, other broadcasters interrupted their exit poll coverage to report on Hong’s 'banned song incident'.

A smile returned to Hong’s face. He shook hands with his supporters one last time, went home,


And then, Hwang crosses the final threshold of votes needed, and his victory is officially confirmed.


And the next day, Hong began preparing to emigrate to Hawaii.

2027 South Korean presidential election - Wikipedia

The 2027 South Korean presidential election was held on March 3, 2027, to elect the 21st president of South Korea. In the election, Min Kyung-wook, former leader of the United Future Party, defeated Kim Doo-kwan, former Governor of South Gyeongsang Province and candidate of the Democratic Party, to become president.

Min Kyung-wook became the first president from Incheon and the first born in the 1960s. He was also seen as the first candidate to win the presidency without distancing himself from his party’s previous president. Kim Doo-kwan made history as the first politician to rise from county governor to presidential candidate. The election result - Min’s victory by a margin of just over 7,000 votes - triggered widespread social unrest. Key issues in the race included political polarization, conspiracy theories surrounding fraud in the 2026 local elections, the Cheong Wa Dae’s restriction of MBC’s press access, debates over renegotiating US-Korea tariffs, low birth rates and aging demographics, and the decline of non-metropolitan regions.

Min Kyung-wook stated, 'We faced a once-in-a-lifetime crisis where our nation could have been stolen by pro-China forces through election fraud. Thankfully, our people stood united and defended liberal democracy. I am deeply grateful.' On the other hand, Kim Doo-kwan, after his defeat was confirmed, responded, 'I don’t know who’s accusing whom of election fraud,' and added, 'If it weren’t for media suppression and early voting restrictions under the Hwang Kyo-ahn administration, I would’ve won by about 500,000 votes.' He announced plans to formally request a recount from the National Election Commission.

2027 South Korean presidential election - Wikipedia

The 2027 South Korean presidential election was held on March 3, 2027, to elect the 21st president of South Korea. In the election, former Seoul Mayor Na Kyung-won of the United Future Party defeated lawmaker Kwak Sang-eon of the Democratic Party to become president.

With her victory, Na Kyung-won became South Korea’s second female president after Park Geun-hye, and the first female president with a legal background. Kwak Sang-eon was the first major party presidential candidate born in the 1970s and is also the son-in-law of former President Roh Moo-hyun. Notably, both candidates shared the same registered hometown: Yeongdong County in North Chungcheong Province. Key issues in the race included mass protests against healthcare policy reforms in 2025-2026, political polarization, conspiracy theories surrounding alleged election fraud in the 2024 general election, the cancellation of the Saemangeum International Airport project, low birth rates and aging demographics, and the decline of non-metropolitan regions.

Na Kyung-won stated, 'It always pained me to think about how much suffering the people endured during the ten years of pro-North dictatorship under Moon Jae-in and Ryu Si-min. I want to promise that I will end all that chaos. We will never go back.' Kwak Sang-eon commented, 'I’m sorry I couldn’t deliver the best outcome in this critical moment. I take full responsibility, so please direct all criticism toward me.' During Kwak’s exit from the press conference, some supporters caused a stir by demanding he reject the election results, sparking controversy.
